  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In the interest of the Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society, Mary Grew inquires about the expediency of engaging Miss Lucy Stone for a few weeks as a lecturer to women. Grew asks for Anne Warren Weston&apos;s opinion and Wendell Phillips&apos;s opinion on this matter; Wendell Phillips is Anne Warren Weston&apos;s cousin. She asks a number of questions regarding Miss Stone, such as: &quot;Does she wear well?&quot; &quot;Is her conversation instructive and interesting to the unenlightened?&quot; She laments the absence of Mrs. Maria Weston Chapman. Preparations for the next fair (in Philadelphia) have begun. Mary Grew comments: &quot;We mean to have a better one than we have ever yet held.&quot; Mary Grew will send the annual report and &quot;a sermon, recently preached by Mrs. [Lucretia] Mott to the medical students of this city.&quot;</subfield>
